{"type":"message","id":"f7286419","parentId":"7c7814bc","timestamp":"2026-03-13T01:08:20.847Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Okay, let's tackle this. The user has a cron job set to check the image generation queue for img-gen-3. The task is to run the img-claim.js script and process any pending requests.\n\nFirst, I need to check the queue by executing the node command. The user mentioned that if a request is returned (not null), I should process it following the SOUL.md workflow. So the first step is to run the script to see if there's any request.\n\nI should start by calling the exec function with the command \"node /data/img-gen/img-claim.js img-gen-3\". This should return the JSON of the next request or null if the queue is empty. \n\nWait, the current time is Friday, March 13th, 2026, 9:08 AM. The cron is set to run at this time. The user's instruction says if a request is returned, process it. So I need to check the queue.\n\nAssuming the command returns a request, then according to the SOUL.md workflow, the next steps are: get the MultiLogin X profile ID, craft the prompt using the Image Prompting Guide, generate the image in Gemini, download it, and mark it as complete with img-complete.js.\n\nBut the user's instruction here is just to check the queue and process any pending requests. So the immediate action is to run the img-claim command.\n\nI need to use the exec tool with the command. Let me structure the tool call properly.\n\nThe command is: node /data/img-gen/img-claim.js img-gen-3\n\nSince this is a cron job, it's likely that the system will handle the output. The response from the script will either be a JSON object with the request details or null.\n\nSo the first step is to execute that command. If the result is not null, then proceed with the steps outlined in SOUL.md.\n\nI should make sure to call exec with the correct command. The working directory is /data/.openclaw/workspace-img-gen-3, but the script